      • Disjunction

        public Disjunction(IProblem[] problemArray)
            throws java.lang.Exception
        Returns an IProblem satisfied if and only if at least one of the following IProblems is satisfied: 
         problemArray[0]
 problemArray[1]
 problemArray[2]
 .
 .
 .
 problemArray[n-1]
 
 where n=problemArray.length.
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception

      • Disjunction

        public Disjunction(IProblem[] problemArray,
                   IBooleanVariable[] booleanVariableArray)
            throws java.lang.Exception
        If 
         problemArray={p_0,p_1,p_2,...,p_{n-1}}
 and
 booleanVariableArray={x_0,x_1,x_2,...,x_{n-2}}
        then Returns an {r_0,r_1,r_2,...,r_{n-2}} where 
         r_0=Disjunction.or(p_0,r_1,x_0)
 r_1=Disjunction.or(p_1,r_2,x_1) 
 r_2=Disjunction.or(p_2,r_3,x_2) 
 .
 .
 .
 r_{n-3}=Disjunction.or(p_{n-3},r_{n-2},x_{n-3})
 r_{n-2}=Disjunction.or(p_{n-2},p_{n-1},x_{n-2})
        In effect, for the first i such that x_i is true, p_i is returned. If no such i exists, p_{n-1} is returned.
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception
